anki: 25.02.5 -> 25.07.2

This includes needing to migrate to a 'uv' based packaging system, since
that's what upstream did.

Unfortunately, `uv sync` as a FoD doesn't work since it's not a stable
output format.

I handled it by writing a hacky "uv.lock to nix" converter (in the form
of the 'update.sh' script), and then using fetchurl to download every
file referenced in the uv.lock.

Using that, combined with the "UV_FIND_LINKS" environment variable lets
uv operate offline, so it seems like that's a good enough solution
there, phew!

The next hurdle was that anki wants us to populate 'pyenv' for an
offline build, and I wasn't sure the exact right 'uv' commands for that.
I ended up with a mix of 'uv export' to make requirements.txt files, and
'uv pip install' to install em. That seems to work okay for most things.

The final problem was that using anki's suggested version of PyQt hits
linker errors. To me, the easiest solution seemed like just using the
already-packaged pyqt packages from nixpkgs, so I did that.

Overall, this feels pragmatic and like it works.

I think the most compelling alternative would be to generate
"requirements.txt" using uv export, relax all the version requirements,
and use nixpkgs-packaged dependencies only.
I ended up not taking that route because not all of anki's dependencies
are present in nixpkgs, and so doing it like done in this PR seemed more
expedient.

That's the notes I have, hopefully this approach seems overall
reasonable!

issue.title: Add aircraft ground position decoding on 1090MHz
issue.body:
Currently, ADSBee only decodes airborne positions for aircraft. It would be good to also report aircraft on the ground along with their associated positions.

This will require a [slightly different CPR decoding implementation](https://mode-s.org/1090mhz/content/ads-b/4-surface-position.html) with a different global grid, as well as a reference position. The reference position could be pulled from some sort of averaged position across multiple airborne aircraft contacts, or from a position that can be input by the user.

issue.title: simplify regexp/grep syntax
issue.body:
This commit cleans up the regexp/grep syntax by isolating the regexp pattern and glob syntax to search expressions and using conventional strings for the functions regexp(), regexp_replace(), and grep().  This allowed us to remove a bunch of special case syntax for these functions from the PEG grammar.

This change means that globbing is no longer available for grep, which now uses only regular expressions.  If we want to allow globbing, we can enable that with a function that converts glob strings to regexps or perhaps introduce a g"glob" style string.

We also removed the implied "this" argument from grep and now require two arguments.

Detailed docs updates are forthcoming in the book branch.

However, there are a few **critical blockers** that must be addressed before approval: 1. **Direct Model Reference Instead of get_user_model()** - In `taxi/forms.py`, the Meta classes for `DriverCreationForm` and `DriverLicenseUpdateForm` reference `Driver` directly. The requirement is to use `get_user_model()` instead. This ensures flexibility if the user model changes and is a core Django best practice. - **How to fix:** Replace: ```python class Meta: model = Driver ``` with: ```python from django.contrib.auth import get_user_model class Meta: model = get_user_model() ``` 2. **Missing Trailing Slashes in URLs** - In `taxi/urls.py`, several URL patterns are missing the required trailing slash (`/`). This is an explicit requirement and can cause routing issues in Django. - **How to fix:** Ensure all URL patterns end with a `/`, for example: ```python path('driver/update//', ...) path('driver/delete//', ...) path('cars//assign/', ...) path('cars//remove/', ...) ``` (Double-check all patterns for compliance.) 3. **Missing 'Cancel' Button on Delete Confirmation Page** - In `templates/taxi/driver_confirm_delete.html`, only a 'Delete' button is present. The checklist requires both a 'Delete' and a 'Cancel' button, with 'Cancel' returning the user to the previous or a safe page (like the driver list or detail page). - **How to fix:** Add a 'Cancel' button, for example: ```html Cancel ``` Or use JavaScript to go back to the previous page if preferred. 4. **View Naming Consistency** - The update view for Driver is named `DriverUpdateForm` instead of the conventional `DriverUpdateView`.
